Revenue from a special consumption
tax will provide the biggest single income item in  Turkey â€™s 2012
budget, rising faster than overall proceeds, Hurriyet newspaper
reported.  The tax on cigarettes, alcohol, mobile phones and cars will
bring in 70.6 billion liras ($38 billion) next year, 15 percent
more than expected this year, the newspaper said. Overall budget
revenue rises 13 percent in 2012, it said, citing plans outlined
by Finance Minister Mehmet Simsek in Ankara.  Income tax will raise 56.7 billion liras and corporate tax
